"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nExecutive Summary\n&#xa0;•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe NFU recognises the importance of antimicrobial resistance as a fundamental threat to animals and humans \nalike.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe NFU believes that antimicrobials are a precious resource and their effectiveness must be protected.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nScientific evidence increasingly recognises that the problem of antimicrobial resistance in humans is a consequence of irresponsible use of \nantimicrobials in human medicine.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMinimising the risk of disease on farm through the development and implementation of farm health planning and disease reduction strategies are an important aspect of reducing the need \nfor\n antimicrobials\n on farm\n. \n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEven wi\nth the best of care however, farm animals will still get sick and may need antimicrobial treatment. \nThese anti\nmicrobials\n are available only with a veterinary prescription and it is the veterinary surgeon who decides what to administer and when to use them.\n The livestock keeper must ensure that these instructions are adhered to\n, as well as meeting regulatory commitments such as recording the use and treatment regime\n.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe NFU fundamentally supports the principle of responsible use of antimicrobials which mea\nns using them as little as possible and as much as necessary.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe NFU feels that \nthe UK’s intervention strategy for reducing the impact and development of \nantimicrobial\n resistance hinge\ns\n around identifying a\nnd avoiding high risk practices, and believes th\nat\n this is where the responsible use principles\n, as developed and promoted by RUMA,\n \nshould be fully supported.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe NFU is opposed to setting targets or level of use restrictions\n, as implemented in some other EU Member States\n. Reducing dosages or the lengt\nh of treatment simply to use a lesser quantity of anti\nmicrobials\n to meet reduction targets is not responsible use. It could in fact encourage the development of \nantimicrobial\n resistance\n,\n compro\nmise animal health and welfare and encourage illegal practices.\n&#xa0;\nIntroduction\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow has antimicrobial resistance developed in the past decade?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat are the gaps in our knowledge about antimicrobial resistance?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nIs there sufficient research and investment into new antibiotics or other treatments and methods to\n ensure continued protection against infection? If not, how could this be rectified?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat measures (including behavioural change) have been most effective in controlling the spread of resistant pathogens, and could such measures be used to \ncontrol other pathogens?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat global coordination and action is required to fight antimicrobial resistance and is the UK contributing enough towards cross-border initiatives?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat are the strengths and weaknesses of the Go\nvernment’s 2013-2018 strategy for tackling antimicrobial resistance? What changes might be made to further strengthen the Government’s action plan?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nNovember 2013\n&#xa0;\n"